text: hi everyone warmth any bed tano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of this new brent
faya's record wasteland this is a brand
new lp from r b singer and songwriter
brent faiz his second in fact a project
i was pretty excited to sink my teeth
into given everything i had heard about
it said that it was more ambitious than
brent's very bland and meandering debut
and believe me i needed a bit of
excitement going into this thing because
truth be told brent is far from the
boldest and strongest voice out there in
the world of r b right now his shy and
boyish vocal lines don't really leave
much of an impression on me nor do they
come off all that alluring or passionate
or heart-wrenching much of the time his
singing i found to be more mild than
anything occasionally his vocal runs do
remind me of artists like samfa for
example but they come across way less
passionate in their delivery and while
the r b landscape has changed pretty
significantly over the past 10 years
with alternative abstract and homespun
sounds being more dominant than ever but
even in this context brent's music to me
has not smacked of anything more than
average so i was hoping wasteland would
be some kind of sea change moment for
brent and while narratively this lp is
definitely a flex sonically it's still
very disappointing with this project we
get a very loosely framed tragic love
story where brent gets his girlfriend
pregnant eventually ends up losing track
of his priorities in the midst of fame
and success and desire then at the end
of the album she pretty much calls him
on the phone and begins to threaten
suicide and things get even uglier from
there now granted this is a more
gripping tale than most artists are
willing to tell on record these days too
bad it's spread over a very bland hour
of music though on this album so bland
in fact it doesn't really complement the
urgency and i think darkness of this
story as brent slowly drifts away from
this woman who clearly needs him after
making her a ton of promises that he
clearly was not ready to keep which
hangs kind of like a dark cloud over
moments on this thing that i guess are
supposed to be bringing some sensual
vibes like all mine though i suppose on
this moment there is an implied element
of sinister selfishness a lot of the
weekend but it doesn't really quite have
that bite or ominous atmosphere that
abel's classic stuff brings we also have
the sickeningly long-winded price of
fame which goes nowhere fast for six
minutes even with a very stark beat
change around the midpoint there's also
ghetto gatsby where alicia keys near
whispered feature
dominates far better than nearly
anything brent does on the track vocally
even drake and the neptunes fail to
breathe life into this very sleepy
record as the track they're featured on
wasting time has some very bland perks
overly aggressive 808s and one of the
most average drizzy verses we've heard
in a minute swear i'm more purple rain
prince than prince charming the
interludes and skits that move the flow
and narrative of this lp along are
pretty nice but there are some songs on
here that feel pretty much like
interludes that overstay their welcome
be that rolling stone or jackie brown
even the track [ __ ] you talking about
it's hard to tell what exactly is the
right vibe or direction for brent to
move in for his music to really hit and
resonate becomes something more than
just merely background music as when the
songs in production match brent's very
low level of energy vocally uh yeah
these tracks really don't do much more
than just be wallpaper but then with
dead man walking where the strings and
some pretty hard-hitting bits of
percussion up the ante a bit brent's
voice begins to get lost in the mix
pretty easily now i will say addictions
and role model do take some pretty
catchy turns on the record as the
narrative of this lp
turns darker and more egotistical the
glamorous keys on bad luck also elevate
things to a higher level and i will give
it to the album overall it ends a lot
stronger than it starts because we do
have that very powerful closing skit on
the record as well as the track angel
which uh is pretty eerie given how the
way the records narrative closes but in
my opinion it's too little too late for
an album whose most standout moment in
its first seven tracks is a tyler the
creator feature overall with this lp i'm
very on the fence there are elements of
it that i think are very clean and
serene well-produced balanced and put
together and overall once more i do like
and respect the narrative that goes into
this thing but by that same token the
songwriting is one-dimensional the
vocals are one-dimensional the lyrics
are predictable the performances are
unmemorable and underwhelming the
features are mostly just okay and don't
really add that much to the overall
narrative of the lp this is obviously
brent's large-scale attempt at doing
something big and the end results don't
really end up being much more than just
tolerable i'm feeling a decent two
strong five on this one tran position
